name: Structure--Hampton Academy (1805)
description:
Two separate Hampton Academy structures occupied this site. The first was opened in 1805 as the public school for Elizabeth City County. From 1845 to 1855, John B. Cary rented the building and operated a private school (also under the name Hampton Academy; in 1855 he opened his Hampton Military Academy nearby). Hampton Academy again was operated as a pubic school until 1861, when it was burned along with the town by local Confederate troops.

name: Structure--Hygeia Hotel
description:
The original Hygeia Hotel was to the north of this site, running along the moat south of Ruckman Road. It was destroyed in 1862. In 1863, owners of the former hotel were granted permission from the Army to build the Hygeia Dining Saloon on this site. It was enlarged as the Hygeia Hotel in 1868 and greatly expanded to the east (covering most of present-day Continental Park) in 1881. It was demolished in 1902 after it was acquired by the owners of the Chamberlin Hotel.

Museum Collections:
http://hampton.pastperfect-online.com/36184cgi/mweb.exe?request=clicksearch;dtype=d;subset=0;_t1104=structure--hygeia%20hotel

name: Structure--Hygeia Hotel (First)
description:

In 1863, owners of the hotel were granted permission to build the Hygeia Dining Saloon to the south, near the wharf; it gradually was expanded into the second Hygeia Hotel.

description:
The Kenneth E. Rice Memorial Museum collected and displayed fossils and other preserved specimens found in the adjacent fossil pit. The fossils and specimens from the Kenneth E. Rice Memorial Museum and Fossil Pit have been identified as part of the Yorktown Formation and classified from the Miocene Age.

name: Structure--King Street Wharf
description:
A wharf has existed here since the colonial era. It served as a major export location for tobacco and import location for supplies and wares entering Virginia. It also served as a customs point for goods traveling up or down the James River. In the late 19th century it served as an Old Dominion Line steamship wharf, and in the 19th and 20th centuries it played a vital role in Hampton's seafood industry.

Museum Collections:
http://hampton.pastperfect-online.com/36184cgi/mweb.exe?request=clicksearch;dtype=d;subset=0;_t1104=structure--king%20street%20wharf

name: Structure--Lake House (King's Arms Tavern)
description:
Also called the "Old Brick House" and the "Whiting House". The structure was originally the Kings Arms Tavern and was likely remodeled into a residence by Kennon Whiting before the Civil War. The house survived the 1861 fire that destroyed most of the town. In the 1880s, J.B. Lake (whose office was next door) bought the house and remodeled it, covering the brick with a layer of wood siding and adding a mansard roof with dormers. The house was torn down in 1966.

name: Structure--Phenix School
description:
Opened in 1931 at Hampton Institute as the George P. Phenix Training School to train teachers and educate local African-American children. In 1940, Hampton Institute leased the building to the Elizabeth City County School Board and the school became part of the County school system (as a segregated African-American school). In 1962, the school was relocated and opened as Phenix High School, after Hampton Institute refused to renew the lease on the building based on Hampton's slowness to respond to the integration requirements resulting from the 1958 Brown v. Board of Education ruling by the Supreme Court. (See also: Structure--Pembroke High School).

name: Structure--Villa Margaret
description:
Constructed in 1855 for Captain Washington I. Newton, who was stationed at nearby Fort Monroe. Purchased and used as a summer home by President John Tyler and his second wife Julia. During the Civil War, the house was used as a barracks and as a school for freedmen. Mrs. Tyler sold the property in 1874, and it was torn down in 1911 (it is believed that building material was salvaged and used for construction of the Dixie Hospital on the site).

Photograph taken by George Stacy during the Civil War:
http://www.loc.gov/pictures/item/2009631322

Description of Sinclair family history and property in Hampton and Gloucester.
http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~vaggsv/issue13_pub.pdf

The winter home of Jefferson B. Sinclair. According to Girard Chambers, Jr., the home was located "formerly in center of Plaza Drive about in front of house No. 9[.] It was one story frame, with dormers in roof, it faced Rip Rap Road. It was carted away piece by piece during Civil War. Slave cabins were at 1010 N. King St. and barn was at 1016 N. King St. One slave cabin was still standing when my father bought 3 acres of land in 1904."
